title: space
text:
Today is January 9th, we’re working with the ’Objects Launched into Space” data from April 23, 2024 from Tidy Tuesday.


Code
library(dplyr)



Attaching package: 'dplyr'


The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':

    filter, lag


The following objects are masked from 'package:base':

    intersect, setdiff, setequal, union


###1. import the data


Code
# Option 1: tidytuesdayR package 
## install.packages("tidytuesdayR")
tuesdata <- tidytuesdayR::tt_load('2024-04-23')

Code
#What's the relationship between entity and code? is there a 1-1 relationship?


###3. Transform


Code
#outer_space_objects |> filter(Year == min(Year))

#It appears that the entity 'world' is an aggregated sum of all the objects released that year. It may be not useful for plotting or aggregating statistics, so we'll create our own table 'space' that doesn't the Entity of 'world' in it.

space <- outer_space_objects |> filter(Entity != 'World')

#I also want to make the distinction bewteen countries and non-countries.
space$Country <- dplyr::if_else(is.na(space$Code), true = 'Non-Country', false = 'Country')


####The prompt for today are:

When did each entity start launching objects into space?

We can get started with these prompts and then see what else we might be interested in. Maybe even some projections?
###4. Visualize


Code
library(ggplot2)


Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 4.2.3


Code
ggplot(space |> group_by(Entity) |> slice(which.min(Year)),
       aes(x = Year, y = num_objects, group = Entity, label = Entity)) + 
  geom_jitter() + 
  geom_text() +
  theme_bw()






What years saw the biggest increase in space object launches?



Code
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(space |> group_by(Year) |> summarize(total = sum(num_objects)),
       aes(x = Year, y = total)) + 
  geom_jitter() + 
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = 'Year', y = 'Total Objects', title = 'Total Number of Objects Launched Per Year')






What’s interesting about this is the question: `What entity is contributing to the sudden increase of the total number of objects launched per year?’. We can also attempt to numerically calculate the percentage change each year in the total number of objects, and also group it by entity!



Code
#As there are a lot of entities and countries, it may be good to create some distinction between countries/entities that launch a lot of things vs not alot.

total_df <- space |> group_by(Entity) |> summarize(total = sum(num_objects))

total_df


# A tibble: 109 × 2
   Entity     total
   <chr>      <dbl>
 1 APSCO          1
 2 Algeria        6
 3 Angola         2
 4 Arabsat       15
 5 Argentina     22
 6 Armenia        1
 7 Australia     47
 8 Austria        3
 9 Azerbaijan     3
10 Bangladesh     2
# ℹ 99 more rows


There are {r} nrow(total_df[total_df$total == 1, ] out of {r} length(unique(total_df$Entity)) entities that have only launched one object ever. These are not terribly useful.


Code
ggplot(total_df |> filter(total <= 500), aes(x = total)) + geom_histogram()


`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.





Code
#If we plot the total number launched below 500, we can see perhaps an easier filter for what entities to include.

#We'll limit it onlt to entities that have launched over a total of 100 objects


#First let’s look at the same plot we already made but change the color?


Code
library(ggplot2)
space_filtered <- space |> group_by(Entity) |> mutate(total = sum(num_objects)) |> filter(total >= 100)

ggplot(space_filtered,
       aes(x = Year, y = num_objects, fill = Entity)) + 
  geom_histogram(position = 'stack', stat = 'identity') + 
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = 'Year', y = 'Total Objects', title = 'Total Number of Objects Launched Per Year')


Warning in geom_histogram(position = "stack", stat = "identity"): Ignoring
unknown parameters: `binwidth`, `bins`, and `pad`


Warning in vp$just: partial match of 'just' to 'justification'







Code
#Calculate percentage change per year for these 15 entities.
#We can see that there's only a record listed for when something was launched, so for years where there was no launch the number remained the same. We'll have to create a dataframe that has all the years filled in.
space_full <- expand.grid(seq(min(space_filtered$Year), max(space_filtered$Year), by = 1),
            unique(space_filtered$Entity))
names(space_full) <- c('Year', 'Entity')
space_full['Number'] <- 0
space_full <- left_join(space_full, space_filtered |> select(Year, Entity, num_objects), by = c("Year", 'Entity'))
space_full$num_objects[is.na(space_full$num_objects)] <- 0

delta_df <- space_full |> group_by(Entity, Year) |> mutate(running_total = cumsum(num_objects)) |> mutate(delta = (running_total-lag(running_total))/running_total)

#percentage change from year to year




Code
library(plotly)


Warning: package 'plotly' was built under R version 4.2.3



Attaching package: 'plotly'


The following object is masked from 'package:ggplot2':

    last_plot


The following object is masked from 'package:stats':

    filter


The following object is masked from 'package:graphics':

    layout


Code
library(ggplot2)

accumulate_by <- function(dat, var) {
  var <- lazyeval::f_eval(var, dat)
  lvls <- plotly:::getLevels(var)
  dats <- lapply(seq_along(lvls), function(x) {
    cbind(dat[var %in% lvls[seq(1, x)], ], frame = lvls[[x]])
  })
  dplyr::bind_rows(dats)
}

fig_df <- delta_df |> accumulate_by(~Year)
# fig_df <- fig_df |> group_by(frame) |> mutate(id = row_number())
# delta_df$id <- seq.int(nrow(delta_df))

#delta_df

#we basically need to make 'intermediate' plots for this, and each intermediate plot would be indicated as frame X out of frame Y.
#The first plot would only have the first year, then the second plot the data from years 1 and 2, so on.

#There are 67 years, ranging from 1957 to 2023


g1 <- ggplot(fig_df,
       aes(x = Year, y = running_total, frame = frame, color = Entity)) + 
  geom_line(stat = 'identity') 
  #geom_point() +
  # geom_text(data = 
  #              space_filtered |> group_by(Entity) |> mutate(Total = cumsum(num_objects)) |> filter(Year == last(Year)),
  #      aes(label = Entity),
  #      show.legend = FALSE) +
  # theme_bw() +
  # labs(x = 'Year',
  #      y = 'Total',
  #      title = 'Total Objects Launched from 1957 - 2023')


fig <- ggplotly(g1) 

fig %>% animation_opts(
  frame = 300, 
  transition = , 
  redraw = FALSE
)

title: parfumo

Today is Thursday, December 12th and I’m working on this weeks’ tidy tuesday dataset sourced from Parfumo.
My goals for today are to continue to practise using dplyr::across and dplyr::map functions, and to create some visualizations using packages I’ve not used before!

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)

# Option 1: tidytuesdayR package 
## install.packages("tidytuesdayR")
# tuesdata <- tidytuesdayR::tt_load('2024-12-10')

tuesdata <- tidytuesdayR::tt_load(2024, week = 50)

parfumo_data_clean <- tuesdata$parfumo_data_clean

# Option 2: Read directly from GitHub

Immediately we can see that quite a large number of perfumes have missing information, such as concentration, the notes, and perfumers. We can look to see if the missingness is correlated across variables. We can plot this using a correlation matrix.


Code
parfumo_missing <- parfumo_data_clean %>%
  mutate(across(Concentration:Perfumers, ~ !is.na(.), .names = "{.col}_missing"))

missing_cor_df <- cor(parfumo_missing |> select(contains('Missing')))
range(missing_cor_df)


[1] 0.01594804 1.00000000


Correlation ranges from 0.0159 to 1, no negative correlations.


Code
#install.packages('ggcorrplot')
library(ggcorrplot)
ggcorrplot::ggcorrplot(missing_cor_df, type = 'lower', colors = c('white', 'pink', 'red'))





The good news is that it looks like if any of the notes are missing, the the other notes are missing as well. The rating count and rating value are also highly correlated, which is unsurprising as well.


Code
#Since there are a lot of text for the main accords, we'll have to make it long format when we split up the main accords.
#if we're only looking at accords, we can make it into a long dataframe
accords_vec <- parfumo_data_clean |> filter(!is.na(Rating_Value)) |> 
  mutate(accords = strsplit(as.character(Main_Accords), split = ", ")) |> 
  tidyr::unnest(accords)


The prompts today are:
1. What factors most influence the rating of a perfume?
2. Are there distinct scent families that dominate the market, and how are they perceived by users?
3. Has the popularity of certain fragrance notes evolved over time?


Code
#If I want to have a plot of the range of values and accords
ggplot(data = accords_vec, aes(x = Rating_Value, y = accords, fill = accords)) + geom_boxplot() + theme_bw() + labs(x = 'Rating Value', y = 'Accords', title = 'Distribution of Ratings Across Accords')

Let’s start with just looking at the number of border crossings across time by land border region


Code
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(cbp_state, aes(x = month_abbv, y = encounter_count, fill = land_border_region)) +
  geom_histogram(stat = 'identity') + 
  theme_bw() + 
  facet_grid(.~ fiscal_year) + 
  labs(x = 'Time', y = 'Count', title = 'Number of Border Crossings Across FY2020 - FY2024 by Land Border Region') + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::unit_format(unit = "K", scale = 1e-4))





If we wanted to plot the number of encounters on a map by state, how would we do that?


Code
# library(tidycensus)
# 
# #getting tidycensus data
# geography_df <- get_acs(
#   variables = "B19013_001",
#   geography = "state",
#   geometry = TRUE,
#   year = 2020
# )
# 
# geography_df$state_abbr <- state.abb[match(geography_df$NAME, state.name)]
# 
# #add the geography information to the cbp_state data
# 
# cbp_state$geometry <- geography_df$geometry[match(cbp_state$state, geography_df$state_abbr)]
# 
# #Now we can generate the plot
# 
# cbp_grouped <-  cbp_state |> group_by(fiscal_year, geometry) |> summarize(total = sum(encounter_count)) |> sf::st_sf()
# 
# ggplot(cbp_grouped, aes(fill = total)) +
#   geom_sf(color = NA) +
#   facet_wrap(~fiscal_year)


Pretty ugly but at least we got somewhere as a starting point.
Now maybe let’s work on the prompts…
Prompts from Tidy Tuesday:
1. How has the implementation (and potential end) of Title 42 affected migration and enforcement trends compared to Title 8 actions?
If we look at things from the state level…


Code
ggplot(cbp_state |> mutate(Date = lubridate::ym(paste(fiscal_year, month_abbv))) |> 
         group_by(Date, title_of_authority, land_border_region) |> 
         summarize(total = sum(encounter_count)),  
         aes(x = Date, y = total, color = title_of_authority, shape = land_border_region)) +
  geom_point(stat = 'identity') + 
  geom_line() + 
  theme_bw() + 
  facet_wrap(~ land_border_region) + 
  labs(x = 'Time', y = 'Count', title = 'Number of Border Crossings Across FY2020 - FY2024 by Land Border Region') + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::unit_format(unit = "K", scale = 1e-4))





it looks like there are some yo-yo and reactionary trends, it could be related to court decisions. Almost entirely restricted to the Southwest Land Border.
If we look at people with the same citizenship trying to cross at the north vs south borders, what would that look like?


Code
ggplot(cbp_state |> 
         filter(citizenship %in% c("INDIA", "CHINA, PEOPLES REPUBLIC OF", "OTHER")) |> 
         mutate(Date = lubridate::ym(paste(fiscal_year, month_abbv))) |> 
         group_by(Date, title_of_authority, land_border_region, citizenship) |> 
         summarize(total = sum(encounter_count)),  
         aes(x = Date, y = total, color = title_of_authority, shape = land_border_region)) +
  geom_point(stat = 'identity') + 
  geom_line() + 
  theme_bw() + 
  facet_wrap(citizenship ~ land_border_region) + 
  labs(x = 'Time', y = 'Count', title = 'Number of Border Crossings Across FY2020 - FY2024 by Land Border Region') + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::unit_format(unit = "K", scale = 1e-4))





Code
ggplot(cbp_state |> 
         filter(citizenship %in% c("MEXICO", "VENEZUELA", "GUATEMALA", "HAITI")) |> 
         mutate(Date = lubridate::ym(paste(fiscal_year, month_abbv))) |> 
         group_by(Date, title_of_authority, land_border_region, citizenship) |> 
         summarize(total = sum(encounter_count)),  
         aes(x = Date, y = total, color = title_of_authority, shape = land_border_region)) +
  geom_point(stat = 'identity') + 
  geom_line() + 
  theme_bw() + 
  facet_wrap(citizenship ~ land_border_region) + 
  labs(x = 'Time', y = 'Count', title = 'Number of Border Crossings Across FY2020 - FY2024 by Land Border Region') + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::unit_format(unit = "K", scale = 1e-4))





While we see Mexico with overwhelmingly the number of denied border crossings, the pattern exhibited for Mexico is unlike the pattern for any other country, at any other land border.


Code
ggplot(cbp_state |> 
         filter(citizenship %in% c("MEXICO") & land_border_region == 'Southwest Land Border') |> 
         mutate(Date = lubridate::ym(paste(fiscal_year, month_abbv))) |> 
         group_by(Date, title_of_authority, demographic) |> 
         summarize(total = sum(encounter_count)),  
         aes(x = Date, y = total, color = title_of_authority)) +
  geom_point(stat = 'identity') + 
  geom_line() + 
  theme_bw() + 
  facet_wrap(~demographic) + 
  labs(x = 'Time', y = 'Count', title = 'Number of Border Crossings Across FY2020 - FY2024 by Land Border Region') + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::unit_format(unit = "K", scale = 1e-4))

It looks like the number of medals has a fair number of missingness. If it’s missing does that mean that someone didn’t get the medal?




Code
olympics$age_na <- as.numeric(is.na(olympics$age))
olympics$height_na <- as.numeric(is.na(olympics$height))
olympics$weight_na <- as.numeric(is.na(olympics$weight))

#Is missingness associated with year?
olympics_na_df <- olympics |> 
         group_by(year, sport) |> 
         summarize(height_na_prop = sum(height_na)/n(),
                   weight_na_prop = sum(weight_na)/n(),
                   age_na_prop = sum(age_na)/n()) |> 
  tidyr::pivot_longer(cols = height_na_prop:age_na_prop,
                      names_to = 'biometric',
                      values_to = 'prop')


It appears that the rate of missingness drastically goes down after ~1960.





Code
ggplot(olympics_na_df |> filter(sport == 'Swimming'),
  aes(x = year, y = prop, color = sport)) +
    geom_point() + facet_grid(.~ biometric) +
  labs(x = 'Year',
       y = 'Proportion',
       title = 'Biometric Missingness Proportion by Year (Swimming Only)')





Age, height, and weight all have a fair bit of missingness as well. Conclusion: To make things easier, let’s just focus on a single sport (swimming) for now.




Plot an animated plot of how age, height, and weight changes across years for 100 metres freestyle swimming (practise previously learned animated plot).
Predictive modelling for who will win the gold for future years? The total number of medals for future years? For this I’ll want to use sports with the longest complete lookback period. Not sure that participant biometrics matters?



Let’s see what the trends are across the 3 biometrics (age, height, weight) for 100 metres freestyle swimming across time for men and women.


Code
swim_100_men_df <- olympics |> filter(sport == 'Swimming' & year >= 1960) |> filter(event == 'Swimming Men\'s 100 metres Freestyle') |> select(age, height, weight, year, medal) |> mutate(medalist = dplyr::if_else(is.na(medal), true = '0', false = '1')) |> mutate(Sex = 'Men')


swim_100_women_df <- olympics |> filter(sport == 'Swimming' & year >= 1960) |> filter(event == 'Swimming Women\'s 100 metres Freestyle') |> select(age, height, weight, year, medal) |> mutate(medalist = dplyr::if_else(is.na(medal), true = '0', false = '1')) |> mutate(Sex = 'women')

swim_100_df <- rbind(swim_100_men_df, swim_100_women_df)

swim_100_df$medalist <- factor(swim_100_df$medalist, levels = c('1', '0'), labels = c('Medalist', 'Non-Medalist'))

#we can plot 'univariate' plots for now
ggplot(swim_100_df, aes(x = year, y = age, color = as.factor(medalist))) + 
  geom_jitter() + 
  facet_grid(.~ Sex) +
  labs(x = 'Year',
       y = 'Age',
       title = 'Changes in Age of Medalist vs Non-Medalist for Swimming From 1960 to 2016') +
  theme_bw()





Code
ggplot(swim_100_df, aes(x = year, y = height, color = as.factor(medalist))) + 
  geom_jitter() + 
  facet_grid(.~ Sex) +
  labs(x = 'Year',
       y = 'Height',
       title = 'Changes in Height of Medalist vs Non-Medalist for Swimming From 1960 to 2016') +
  theme_bw()





Code
ggplot(swim_100_df, aes(x = year, y = weight, color = as.factor(medalist))) + 
  geom_jitter() + 
  facet_grid(.~Sex) +
  labs(x = 'Year',
       y = 'Weight',
       title = 'Changes in Weight of Medalist vs Non-Medalist for Swimming From 1960 to 2016') +
  theme_bw()





It appears that age of winners is middle of the road, but height and weight seems to be trending higher.

We’re running into a situation where the gold medalists’ values appears to be obscured sometimes by the non-winners. Is there a way to always make them appear on top? It appears there used to be an ‘order’ aesthetic in ggplot but it’s since been deprecated. Now you can just arrange your data to achieve the same outcome.
I want to: 1. make the gold medalist points bigger

create cloud/ellipses around distributions
lower the alpha of the individual points?



Code
g2 <- ggplot(fig_df |> arrange(desc(medalist)) |> distinct(),
       aes(x = height, y = weight, frame = year, color = medalist, fill = medalist, alpha = medalist, size = medalist, label = year)) + 
  # annotate(geom="text", x=3, y=30,
  #             color="red") +
  geom_jitter() +
  geom_density_2d(
  data = fig_df |> filter(medalist == 'Non-Medalist'),
  aes(x = height, y = weight, frame = year)) +
  scale_color_manual(
    values = c('Non-Medalist' = 'grey70',
               'Medalist' = 'orange')
  ) +
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = c('Non-Medalist' = 'grey70',
               'Medalist' = 'orange')
  ) +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_alpha_discrete(range = c(1, 0.4)) +
  scale_size_manual(
    values = c('Non-Medalist' = 1,
               'Medalist' = 3)) +
  labs(x = 'Height (cm)',
       y = 'Weight (kg)',
       title = 'Changes in Height and Weight from 1960 to 2016 in 100 Metre Freestyle Swimming') +
  facet_grid(. ~ Sex)

fig_better <- ggplotly(g2)

fig_better






Summary: I was able to create an animated visualization (goal 1 completed). The contours is created using 2D kernal density estimation,
Future things to work on:

Play around more with animations.
Explore ellipses or other ways to show changes in distribution of data across time?

title: olympics
text:
Plot an animated plot of how age, height, and weight changes across years for 100 metres freestyle swimming (practise previously learned animated plot).
Predictive modelling for who will win the gold for future years? The total number of medals for future years? For this I’ll want to use sports with the longest complete lookback period. Not sure that participant biometrics matters?



Let’s see what the trends are across the 3 biometrics (age, height, weight) for 100 metres freestyle swimming across time for men and women.


Code
swim_100_men_df <- olympics |> filter(sport == 'Swimming' & year >= 1960) |> filter(event == 'Swimming Men\'s 100 metres Freestyle') |> select(age, height, weight, year, medal) |> mutate(medalist = dplyr::if_else(is.na(medal), true = '0', false = '1')) |> mutate(Sex = 'Men')


swim_100_women_df <- olympics |> filter(sport == 'Swimming' & year >= 1960) |> filter(event == 'Swimming Women\'s 100 metres Freestyle') |> select(age, height, weight, year, medal) |> mutate(medalist = dplyr::if_else(is.na(medal), true = '0', false = '1')) |> mutate(Sex = 'women')

swim_100_df <- rbind(swim_100_men_df, swim_100_women_df)

swim_100_df$medalist <- factor(swim_100_df$medalist, levels = c('1', '0'), labels = c('Medalist', 'Non-Medalist'))

#we can plot 'univariate' plots for now
ggplot(swim_100_df, aes(x = year, y = age, color = as.factor(medalist))) + 
  geom_jitter() + 
  facet_grid(.~ Sex) +
  labs(x = 'Year',
       y = 'Age',
       title = 'Changes in Age of Medalist vs Non-Medalist for Swimming From 1960 to 2016') +
  theme_bw()





Code
ggplot(swim_100_df, aes(x = year, y = height, color = as.factor(medalist))) + 
  geom_jitter() + 
  facet_grid(.~ Sex) +
  labs(x = 'Year',
       y = 'Height',
       title = 'Changes in Height of Medalist vs Non-Medalist for Swimming From 1960 to 2016') +
  theme_bw()





Code
ggplot(swim_100_df, aes(x = year, y = weight, color = as.factor(medalist))) + 
  geom_jitter() + 
  facet_grid(.~Sex) +
  labs(x = 'Year',
       y = 'Weight',
       title = 'Changes in Weight of Medalist vs Non-Medalist for Swimming From 1960 to 2016') +
  theme_bw()





It appears that age of winners is middle of the road, but height and weight seems to be trending higher.

We’re running into a situation where the gold medalists’ values appears to be obscured sometimes by the non-winners. Is there a way to always make them appear on top? It appears there used to be an ‘order’ aesthetic in ggplot but it’s since been deprecated. Now you can just arrange your data to achieve the same outcome.
I want to: 1. make the gold medalist points bigger

create cloud/ellipses around distributions
lower the alpha of the individual points?



Code
g2 <- ggplot(fig_df |> arrange(desc(medalist)) |> distinct(),
       aes(x = height, y = weight, frame = year, color = medalist, fill = medalist, alpha = medalist, size = medalist, label = year)) + 
  # annotate(geom="text", x=3, y=30,
  #             color="red") +
  geom_jitter() +
  geom_density_2d(
  data = fig_df |> filter(medalist == 'Non-Medalist'),
  aes(x = height, y = weight, frame = year)) +
  scale_color_manual(
    values = c('Non-Medalist' = 'grey70',
               'Medalist' = 'orange')
  ) +
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = c('Non-Medalist' = 'grey70',
               'Medalist' = 'orange')
  ) +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_alpha_discrete(range = c(1, 0.4)) +
  scale_size_manual(
    values = c('Non-Medalist' = 1,
               'Medalist' = 3)) +
  labs(x = 'Height (cm)',
       y = 'Weight (kg)',
       title = 'Changes in Height and Weight from 1960 to 2016 in 100 Metre Freestyle Swimming') +
  facet_grid(. ~ Sex)

fig_better <- ggplotly(g2)

fig_better






Summary: I was able to create an animated visualization (goal 1 completed). The contours is created using 2D kernal density estimation,
Future things to work on:

Play around more with animations.
